The story was mediocre, at best, and not compelling. There was no chemistry between the duo, unlike between Will Smith and Tommy Lee Jones. But at least we spent the entire movie repeatedly showing or telling how much of a gullible moron Chris Hemsworth's character was.  Pathetic. And Thor Ragnarok came out 10/ *3* /17, and in 2017 1+7 is 8. And when both Chris & Tessa were 8, it was 1991. 1+9+9+1= 20. Now we take back that 8 and 1 and then we get 2018 which was when Infinity War came out, and so we take the one again because we just love the one and we add it to that and then we get the year *Endgame* came out and then 2019 minus 2 from the twenty is 2017 which is the year Thor Ragnarok came out. So we replace the 201 in 2017 and use 199 from 1991 and then we get 1997 which is the year the *first* Men in Black  came out. Coincidence? *I* *think* *not* .

text: I don't find it particularly fair that every new version of a classic is criticized just for not being the original (mib, ghostbusters, jurrasic world, star wars, ...). Of course it isn't. Of course there are different actors and different stories. Of course there might be new characters with different skin colors, genders or sexual orientation. Of course there will be mistakes in them. There were mistakes in the originals as well. The originals weren't perfect either, the jokes not always better. We look at these classics through nostalgia glasses that make us overlook what is not so perfect and exaggerate everything that was great about them. Let's give these movies a fair chance. I absolutely love MIB, and I think the trailer looks like this one is going to be fun as well. Let's watch it with an open mind.

text: I seriously don't see why people are being so negative towards this movie. It honestly looks great. To be perfectly fair, I've never seen any of the past MIB movies, but I have a feeling this movie will inspire me to watch them. And also, seeing the original characters in the paintings in this trailer just tells me that this isn't going to be a reboot, but a continuation of the series with new characters and new heroes. And also, I really don't see how having a lead character who is a woman and black is forced diversity or feminism. All I can see is a woman who has discovered the best kept secret in the universe and just wants to prove herself to the MIB. I don't see any forced feminism or diversity, only a woman wanting to prove herself. I seriously believe this movie is going to be good. And Chris Hemsworth along with Tessa Thompson are a good pair for this movie after watching their performance together in Thor 3.

text: I can see why everyone in the comment section is upset as to why there is no Will Smith and Tommy Lee Jones, I was upset too because I associate Will and Tommy with the franchise, but I'm going to guess as to why they aren't in this film. So MiB, is top secret gov't org. and maybe they decided to have different branches in other parts of the world, hence as to why we don't see Will or Tommy. MiB International is showcases a London-based team (I saw the London Eye, so I'm presuming they are a London-based team), hence as to why you see Chris Hemsworth and Tessa Thompson. Only one person reprised their role and that was Emma Thompson, I hope Will and Tommy make a cameo, it would make sense and if not, explain their absence in the film. At least Chris and Tessa have great chemistry due to them performing in a different franchise, Marvel's Thor: Ragnarok. No hate please, I am just explaining it from what I see from this trailer and information on its wikia site. <3 Hopefully I explained it very well, much love <3  Edit: there is an easter egg with Tommy and Will, it is the paintings in the trailer.

text: If I were the writer of this film I would drop the whole comedy and light hearted adventure vibe and go full on horror mystery thriller. I would have the premise be that an agent or agents have been secretly murdered by other agents in MiB and the organization is trying to get to the bottom of an intergalatic whodunnit so they bring in Thompson as an undercover investigator. Hemsworth would be the main suspect. They would go on missions together but there would be that tension of is Hemsworth the traitor? Does he know who Thompson really is? Or is it all a set up? There are so many ways that it could work But instead we get this stale comedy action. Bleh.  Also please stop using super generic hip hop music to make a trailer seem more cool. Not that the actors are bad, but I feel the humor isn’t where I’d like it to be.  That was the fun of the other films: over-the-top sci-fi buddy cop comedy, and it was self-aware of this. text: This is one of the reasons new movies from new screenwriters have become nearly impossible to make & so much of Hollywood can't find work: Because the Majors are reviving decades old franchises that have already run their course in terms of originality whom they assign "studio-approved" writers to. So we get inferior remakes of "The Omen", & "Straw Dogs" & "Carrie" & on and on. The Studios are counting on the fact that if you're under 30, you've still probably not seen most of the decent films that were made in the 70s, 80s & 90s. So now all we have are Sequels & "Prequels" and it's why so many movies flat out s-ck! Look, in all fairness most "Indie" movies I see are simply dreadful. Made by filmmakers for other filmmakers they try to be sooo original & so "Edgy" that they end up being neither. But the majors are now  making sequels to movies whose original barely turned a profit. Just amazing!

text: The studio's didn't even give the original a *full decade* to mature like fine wine before releasing this "money grab" *post-feminist* non-sense. They're coming out with 'reboots' to movies that did extremely with no creative thought whatsoever.   And, fine, if the trailer had lines that were actually *FUNNY*, it would be worth a shot, but the fact that NONE OF THE SCENES were funny, just corny and cheesy with lazy music (not even an original score - i.e. "Here comes the men in black") I hope this movie bombs so you studios learn that your audience are not idiots and you put the time, effort and creativity into your product.   Lastly, the actors lack that 'charm and charisma' that drew you in with the original actors. They may have been able to get away with a poor script, but what made MIB was the chemestry those two brought to the screen that made it special. Here, they found the best looking white guy with NO COMEDIC TIMING who just so happens to be a good character actor and some random black woman to play the role in a movie called MEN in black, not MEN AND WOMEN in black! If you're going to put women as main characters, which I'm all for in the context of a movie, create a new franchise called WOMEN IN BLACK.   This is just virtue signaling, catring to the lowest common denominator. Hollywood. Please, you're shooting yourselves in the foot. You can't FORCE stardom on actors who lack the "It Factor" that makes them stars. If you're going to put people in lead roles, that have to have that special quality that makes them STARS who will draw an audience. No way I would have risked a big-budget film casting a no-name black female actress with no previous comedy background to play a lead role.

text: So let's see, we have a series called "Men in Black", where you now have a woman because, I guess "it's 2019 ya know". What a joke! It's Men in Black, that implies two dudes, particularly Will Smith and Tommy Lee Jones playing their roles. At this point, political correctness is just ruining every established franchise. They may as well just call the title "People in Black" as we don't want to offend anyone. Oh wait... we might offend some people who identify as Attack Helicopters so just call it "Entities in Black Suits" to not offend anyone. /s  I want this to bomb because this is the same as the Ghost Busters reboot, Chris Hemsworth will look like a total bumbling idiot, there for female eye candy and the chick will be the great big "badass" who saves the day. Mark my words, it will happen. At this point, they will reboot everything a part of nerd culture and ruin it by installing women where they do not belong.  Why not make something completely new where women can be badass and it doesn't disrespect an already established franchise that loved? See I didn't like Atomic Blonde, but I never complained because it's not part of an established franchise. So I really have no problem with it as a film. If you want to make a female powerful, go for it, but don't ruin an established franchise for diversity sake. Make a new one and if it's good people will go and watch it. Is it perhaps because you know a movie like that won't do so well, so you tag women into lead roles for already established franchises to get butts in seats? Yes, yes I think it is.

text: To you reading the comments, i say please watch this trailer again with an open mind.  Some of you might have seen nothing but "Mary Sue" Rey all over again, but if you watch with honest eyes, you'll see this character played by Tessa Thompson is very different. She's a rookie actually being mentored by "one of the best ever to wear the suit", he takes all but one of the fight scenes in the trailer, he drives the vehicles, he shows her the ropes.  Yes, she's badass and the recruitment plotline is all about her, but there's nothing to suggest she's "perfect" or that everyone else is "inferior".  Stop it with the post-Star Wars hysteria.

text: Another female character with no flaws or weaknesses.  Boring.  When will they get it right.  If you want people to like a character, especially a female character, she has to have a meaningful struggle against her weakness that knocks her down a couple of times only to have her get back up and pay retribution.  A strong female character is NOT perfect and untouchable, but should have just barely enough strength (with or without help, depending on what kind of story you're telling) to come through a struggle alive while making it believable that failure is a hair's breath away.  Feels like the art of story telling is lost these days.

There is no forcing female leads into there ffs. Stop trying to politicise everything. Just cuz there's 'men' in the name dosent mean it's only reserved for men. text: MIB was never a men only organization and the fact they are taking the reach of such organization "international" it's great, since, you know... They deal with intergalactic/multi-planetary issues, it's just normal MIB has many cells spreaded all over the world.  The idea of making a following up of MIB missions with other agents around the world (in this iteration, London) seems greats to me. About how they look, my only complain is they seem to try to make the main couple to look "cooler" by at some point removing their ties... Which... I like them better with their ties on (just a little detail tbh).  From my point of view this "could" be a "good" movie while the plot and phase of it remain ok.  I don't see the necesity of bringing back WS or TLJ to the film as some sort of protagonists, they already have 3 movies and that's just nostalgia to me in this situation; although a cameo or some sort of "mention" would be cool, I still don't think it is a "necesity" or the movie will be bad without them.  Just keep the flow of the movie natural and don't make it too cringy over sjw agenda and all will be fine.

text: Eh, it might not be too bad--I mean, there are Men in Black other than J, K and Z... some of them are women.  Let's be honest, it does seem weird that an organisation can only do anything if two of its members are doing stuff.  Maybe this can remove a bit of the "J is the chosen one" type magic that makes the three other movies and the cartoon series somewhat irritating to deal with? If it can reduce the "J is the chosen one"--than I am fine with this one.  Also... this movie will be deleting all old copies of Men in Black. After it has been in theatre for a month, you will find all your old DVDs, VHS, Bluray, etc. are now this version of the movie--and only you will know of the previous one. Everybody else having no clue it ever happen. Just a bit of a reminder that the older version will cease to exist upon this one being released.  Still... cannot shake the whole "Straight to home video Disney sequel" vibe I am getting. I mean... some of those movies are not bad--and some are fun to watch (the vend diagram of that is fun too!)... so, I mean... I cannot expect it to be the first Men in Black if I watch it... but...

text: The third MIB is largely argued a flop of sorts. It just wasn't good compared with one and two, while obviously one was by far and large, the very best of the franchise. The reason why it began to be less and less entertaining and less well-received was the fact that they lacked much content overall the further they attempted to extend the series. This also feels too out of place, not for the lack of Will, which is something that goes without saying is weird to say the least, but, it's the fact that they're using two actors which are heavily synonymous with other major movie franchises and characters. They type-casted themselves into specific roles and franchises. Thus, that make this feel really rigid and out of place. But, I hope it will surprise and be great.

text: The concept that made the first film interesting to watch was the interaction between the straitlaced Tommy-lee and Will Smiths excitable rookie character. The dead pan reaction that Tommy-lee had to a lot of the weird and odd things happening in the film just went to emphasize both his experience and that how fantastical we the viewer thinks of the situation that they find themselves in, he has seen bigger and badder. This back and forth between the two characters is what sells the movie. From watching this Trailer it seems that Chris Hemsworth's character is not able to carry out that same bearing. An actor like Colin Firth would have been a better choice in my mind.

TL;DR: This is not Ghostbusters.

text: Agent K: All right, kid, here's the deal. At any given time there are around fifteen hundred aliens on the planet, most of them right here in Manhattan. And most of them are decent enough, they're just trying to make a living.     James: Cab drivers.     Agent K: No, not as many as you'd think. Humans, for the most part, don't have a clue. They don't want one or need one, either. They're happy. They think they have a good bead on things.     James: Why the big secret? People are smart. They can handle it.     Agent K: A person is smart. People are dumb, panicky, dangerous animals and you know it. Fifteen hundred years ago, everybody knew the Earth was the center of the universe. Five hundred years ago, everybody knew the Earth was flat. And fifteen minutes ago, you knew that people were alone on this planet. Imagine what you'll know tomorrow.     James: What's the catch?     Agent K: The catch? The catch is you will sever every human contact. Nobody will ever know you exist anywhere...Ever. I'll give you 'til sunrise to think it over. [walks away]     James: Hey! There were original sci-fi shows with strong women, Aliens (1986), Westworld (2016), Stranger Things (2016), GoT (2011) for example. Can the world just calm itself down and start making decent films again. When was the last time we had a Forest Gump or ET sort of film? A true story telling instead of regurgitated drivel? From London, England.

text: Man am I seeing a lot of people being like, "Oh another shameless reboot" or "No Will Smith = worst movie ever"  Look if I can be that guy for a moment, the trailer itself isn't bad and it at least is trying to live up to the spirit of the original movies. (Unlike the new Ghostbusters and it's trailer) I feel like people should not be so quick to strike things down, unless they're given obvious reasons for why we should be wary of it. Now before someone decides to be that guy and say, "You are apart of the problem!" or "They are trying to cash in on my nostalgia!" First off, I'm a fan of MiB. I grew up with the movies and they are movies I go back to quite a lot. I'm not blindly supporting this, but I am also not quick to just strike it down before it even got a chance to get to the starting line.  As for the "nostalgia" argument. Wouldn't it be MORE "cashing in on our nostalgia" if they DID bring back Will Smith and such for a fourth movie? Or hell, had him in this trailer more than he actually appears in the movie? (Last Jedi anyone?) Here's the thing, am I interested in this movie? Not sure yet, but I'm not turned off by it either. Could it be fun? Could it be good? Who knows, we'll have to see. The most I will say is what I always say to people when a new product and otherwise is announced.  Wait for it to come out, then judge it for yourself. After that, you are fully allowed to say how good/bad it was/is.

text: Ugghh... This looks terrible. Very poorly written & directed by the looks of it. The 1 liners & jokes weren't funny at all, and the Aliens looked very sloppy, non-alien like, and like they were very cheaply thrown together by a shitty CGI Artist. Liam Neeson was a good choice to play the head honcho, but Chris Hemsworth & Tessa Thompson were horrible choices to play the 2 agents. This has 'Money-Grab' written all over it. The Producers obviously didn't take this very seriously. They just rushed everything, and didn't take any time or thought about who they were hiring, and if they were right for the job or not. If they were smart, they would have continued the series with Will Smith & Tommy Lee Jones, and gotten Ed Solomon (who wrote the 1st MIB) to write it. Would have been a great idea, because the 1st MIB has always been the best film in the series, and Ed Solomon hasn't written the script for any MIB movies, since the 1st one.

text: I do not have high hopes for this movie for a few reasons. Whenever I see a trailer for an upcoming movie which proves to be disappointing, there are always a few warning signs, and this one has plenty: 1) Painfully forced pop music. Whenever a trailer has a track of modern music, especially in an adaptation which has nothing to do with it; the studio, marketing, editing, audio department or whoever else is responsible comes off as stupidly tone deaf (e.g. the out of place rap in Assassin's Creed, a franchise whose theme music tends to be subtle and thematic to the setting). Especially when the theme for the earlier movie was already perfect. They even play it here and it sounds far superior to the crap later. 2) Forced humour (movies nowadays appear to be AFRAID of being serious. Yes, MiB isn't a high end spy drama, but the humour is cringe inducing rather than funny). Especially since it reminds me of Thor: Ragnarok rather than MiB when the director is no Taeka Waititi.  3) Bandwagon actor casting (when an actor or actress appears in a good or at least popular movie related to popular culture, EVERYONE seems to want them to give some credibility to the next money grab). This looks more like an alternate universe's interpretation of a boring Thor:Ragnarok. 4) Unfinished effects. Just look at the Justice League. If the effects are incomplete in the trailer, or are updated BETWEEN them, don't expect a well polished product. (Also, expect some unwanted updates as well, such as switching the blue sky to an ugly red) 5) Re-casting (if a previous cast, especially one which worked well isn't present, you tend to lose faith in it. Even if the characters are changed, it can come off as a cop-out). Also, the previous cast worked off well together. K was a no nonsense old timer and J was a fresh rookie but he respected K for his experience and K trusted J's talent and potential to be succesful as his partner and replacement. Thor here comes off as a lazy pretty boy and valkyrie is just another annoying hipster. 6) Winking at the camera. Unless your character is MEANT to do that, winking at the camera with continuity jokes, ESPECIALLY in a reboot comes off as desperate. 7) Unnecessary changes. You shift locations, but there must be a legitimate reason outside of sight seeing. If it is meant to be a reboot, go all the way instead of showing off the previous locations and characters to establish a previous continuity. If it is meant to be a continuation, do that, show and tell another story but make it good. This is too stale to be a reboot and too different to be a sequel. 8) Director quality. When your director is most famous for a Fast and Furious movie which will soon fade from memory, there is a good chance this will too. A movie can survive a couple or more of such warning flags. This trailer however hits ALL of them. A shitty movie can have a great trailer (the Last Jedi), and vice versa but those are exceptions. This doesn't appear to be one. It just gets worse when I watch it again.

They have forsaken  the right way  and gone astray,  following the way of Balaam  the son of Beor  who loved the wages of unrighteousness;  But he was rebuked for his iniquity;  a dumb donkey  speaking with a man's voice  restrained the madness  of the prophet. This whole Force is Female crap IS Kathleen Kennedy’s fault. I don’t care if it’s The Women in Black from Sony or “Fival Goes West And Genderless” or GhostBuster Disaster of the Chris Helmsworth type. It’s getting ridiculous and majorly desperate of these studios. “What can we do for a cash grab this year” “Oh, I know! The EXACT Same story but a worst version of it... but with women versions INSTEAD” “Ooooo I like your thinking Kath. It’$ going to be a  $ucce$$!”  If you don’t see this happening, well, you’re their perfect audience and Kathleen Kennedy thanks you from her yacht off the Hawaiian Islands.   As for me, I’m getting soooo tired of it and think I’m going to go plant a garden instead. True, a garden is as predictable but at least I get free food out of it. And Kathleen Kennedy can never ruin my favorite garden franchises. The Plants Are Not Female.  When do we get men versions of women stories?!? I can’t wait for for the Little Women sequel of the cash grab title “Little Men.” Or what about Kathleen Kennedy’s newest creation The Little Merman. Sounds more like a porno hahaha. Sigh. No more of these crappy films. Will Smith is probably rolling over in his grave after seeing this from heaven

text: *I'm upset. My movie got denied by Hollywood. It was a masterpiece. :,(*  It was about a young boy, named Timmy, who decided to go bowling one day.   But he got beat up by some guys for being gay. :( Timmy's big brother couldn't protect him because he went missing 5 years ago when he was out to get some milk at a 7 11. :( Anywayssssss....  Then Timmy went to school principle to tell on them.  The principle decided to make the boy and the group of bullies work on a group project together. The project was to learn how to build a bridge.  The bullies ended up beating him up again till the boy said "Stop! I'm gay. That doesn't mean you have to beat me up >:, (*  The bullies decided to beat him up some more till one of the bullies, named Chad, said "Guys. We need to do the project or else we have to repeat the 11th grade."  Everyone including Timmy worked on the project together. One of the bullies, named Tyrone, couldn't understand the project. Timmy told him and Derrick said "thanks G". That made Timmy smile. He became a "G." :3  A few seconds later, Derrick said: "G ... for Gay!" And everyone beated on Timmy again. But Timmy kept on smiling. :,)  Timmy kept on helping everyone with building the bridge. Derrick and Chad and the rest of the bullies were amazed how smart Timmy was.   "Hey, maybe we were too harsh on you." said Derrick.   Everyone smiled.  Timmy: "Maybe this bridge is more than a project. Maybe it is a metaphor to connect us and help us be friends."  Everyone except Timmy frowned.  Timmy: "Or maybe it is a lame project."  Everyone smiled again.  Then all of a sudden!!!!....Chad's drunk father came out of no where and struck Chad!  Everyone came rushing to Chad. Chad was dying. But he wanted to speak to Timmy. He said to Timmy:   "I'm sorry Timmy. Being gay is ok. Being a bully is not ok. It is gay to be a bully. People who bully gay people are gay. No. I mean. They just suck. But I have to tell you something."  Timmy: "What?" :, (  Chad: "I'm your big brother."  Everyone gasped.  Timmy: "why didn't you come home when you went out to get the milk 5 years ago?" :, (  Chad : "Wait!!! I thought mom wanted some O.J."  Chad died right after saying that.  Timmy cried. Derrick cried. The rest of the bullies cried.  *In conclusion...*  Timmy decided to be the leader of the bullies that day. Everyone accepted Timmy as their new leader.  Chad's father was sent to prison.   Derrick died 1 week later from pimples.  Before he died, he told Timmy that was he was gay. He wanted Timmy to keep it as a secret.  ....Timmy didn't.   Title of the movie: *Timmy, Chad, and his Drunk Dad.*

The first one was great, the second one terrible, and the third one a fun but ultimately forgettable film. This one is a fresh change of pace with the new cast, and despite the obvious tonal shift at least they are trying to reboot it and change things up a bit. There have been plenty of terrible trailers to great films, and great trailers to bad films, so in the meantime we can take this one with a grain of salt and judge it upon seeing it one day.

text: I have a theory, what if she is Will Smith’s daughter? Because maybe his character had fallen in love and he could’ve possibly wanted a life with the woman he fell in love with. Similar to Agent K, in the beginning of the third movie we see him living a normal life but, he never truly forgot what it was like being in the Agency. So, let’s say this movie is set far of into the future. And if Will did decide to settle down maybe he didn’t forget about the agency. Which is why he might’ve taught his daughter some of things she might need to know in order to survive (with aliens and humans). Since aliens often portray as humans I assume they would watch over her if they knew who Will was. Maybe she eventually caught on to the secret. Which is why as she got older she managed to figure it out. I assume something happened like maybe Will had passed and she decided to join MIB b/c she knew that she had a place for her as a legacy.

My only issue with the trailer is that they didn't show more crazy aliens. Also, I hope Will Smith will get a cameo of some sort in the movie. If they stick to the formula of the old movies while not being dull, this has great chances of working out well. I don't expect it to be a masterpiece of any sort, but I think it can be an average or even good fun movie to watch next Summer.

text: Y'all gotta stop with the "It's MEN in black" argument. The title men in black comes from a conspiracy of creepy men dressed in black suits showing up to confront/harass people that claim to have seen something extraterrestrial. The conspiracy arose in the late 1940s (at a time when government agents were all men). This is what inspired the series but the agency now exists in 2018 (when now women and men work the same jobs), the title is not meant to reflect the gender of the agents. So chill out and try not to be so cynical.

text: Sigh... Wasn't *MIB III* enough? 🤦 They managed to rebuild some good will in the series after *II's* weaker reception with K's past + revealing how he & J shared a bond even before they were partners.     I can guarantee you right now, even if Smith and Jones cameo, this isn't going to match, let alone surpass the success of its predecessors. And even if it does, it won't reignite the franchise long-term.    The story was DONE, this "expansion" is a textbook cash grab scenario. When will people learn that sometimes, the best way to respect something we love is knowing when to leave good things ALONE?    Seriously, how many IP's need to be rebooted to laughable or disappointing reception before that age-old lesson sinks in? My guess is, most probably won't take the hint anytime soon and that's sad.

text: Ok,. so I see a lot of people with little faith and no explanation. So let me try and put a finger on the issues people have. First oiff, sony. Second, What bothers me most is the callbacks. What new things does this movie show or hint at? Exactly, nothing. Flying and transformative vehicles, hidden guns, neuralizers, we've seen it all before.And the way the movie keeps shoving it down our throats it feels like nostalgia pandering. And third the plot it self...what is it exactly? The first 3 MIBs were straigh foreward. Buddycop movies that were about cathing one alien badguy.With the dynamic between the agents as the focus. But this? What is the dynamic exactly? I couldn't make it out. All in all this trailer is so bland, it tells us nothing but what the characters look like.Congrats. I won't see this movie. And I'll wait for the reviews before it touvh this thing with a 10 foot pole.

text: Once upon a time, in a far away swamp, there lived an ogre named Shrek (Mike Myers) whose precious solitude is suddenly shattered by an invasion of annoying fairy tale characters. They were all banished from their kingdom by the evil Lord Farquaad (John Lithgow). Determined to save their home -- not to mention his -- Shrek cuts a deal with Farquaad and sets out to rescue Princess Fiona (Cameron Diaz) to be Farquaad's bride. Rescuing the Princess may be small compared to her deep, dark secret.

text: MIB was good because it was about a character whose life changed, and who worked hard to deal with the changes. Movies require a struggle.  Not a goal, not intensity, not action, not happenings and events, not situations, not setups and results, not comedy, not cinematography, not things the main characters need to get done where they sometimes succeed and sometimes fail.  Struggle.  We humans empathize with struggle because we ourselves want to struggle.  We look up to those who have struggled; and we watch those who have begun to struggle with hope and anticipation.  Instead, this movie has another black woman who has no character development throughout the entire film because the creators were afraid to let black people and women make mistakes that people can learn from. When there's no character development, the only thing that could make the movie good is story progression.  But it looks like there's none of that either, because the characters were always rushing to catch up with the story, which means the story has no time to sit and wait for a development. This movie has no struggle.  This is also clearly trying to be another expanded universe, at least of a sort.  The problem is that this trailer hasn't demonstrated that the universe even allows struggle at all.  That means there won't be any interest in any sequels.  A universe without struggle is a universe without opportunity is a universe without potential.  On the bright side, people can't blame the actors.  It's clearly Sony's fault.

text: The first movie worked because it was both funny and thrilling (Your world is going to end - double blink). With each sequel, they rolled with funny and dropped the threat, and they got silly instead (Agent Zed doing floating kung fu kicking??).  Where's the threat of The Bug like monster here that grounded the goofier parts of the first film? It seems everyone is there just to have an attitude and a good time.  Will Smith played it cool but it was funny watching him mess up as he stepped into a world he didn't understand.  This film just looks run of the mill, just like the disappointing MIB2 that got the best parts of the first film so wrong. This new one looks fun, for sure, but nothing in the trail suggested there was a genuine threat, given how the cast look too cool for school.  Maybe there's more to come and it'll not play out like the other sequels but so far... 🤔 meh?

text: I’m really excited for this, been on a MIB marathon for the past few days and this is looking good imo. Love the ascetic, musical choice, more sifi tone, it’s looking good imo. Also Sony, don’t even pretend you’re not referencing Thor, I see that hammer.  But seriously, what’s with the hate, some of it is partially justified but others is just stupid people being stupid.  Like any of you talking about a title change or how a female lead goes against the franchise. Did you even watch the MIB films, The ending of 1 had the girl from the morgue become agent L and J’s partner. Female agents were shown working at MIB in headquarters in scenes throughout the whole trilogy. And O was a secondary character in MIB 3. The organisation is called MIB, hence the title, and that monicker is based off the creepypasta of the Men in Black. MIB doesn’t require being a dude. I’m no SJW or anything but seriously the hate isn’t necessary.  The only criticism I’ve seen that I’ll even slightly accept (although I haven’t seen anyone properly express it) is the whole Hollywood originally thing. To which I say, Firstly this is a spin-off, not a reboot, your MIB is still cannon. Secondly, MIB is already a big franchise with 3 films, games, and a TV show, and it’s a unique franchise at that, going for a sifi-buddy cop comedy genre, with spy and camp elements. Imo that mix of genres is pretty rare, so why are you mad we’re getting more of it. If you’re mad at this then be mad at everything that came after MIB 1.

text: This... actually doesn't look half bad. It's actually pretty neat seeing a new division to the MIB universe while still showing it is in the same universe as the original three. The tone at least from this trailer seems to go back to the first MIB, which the second and third failed to recreate. After Thor Ranarok, it is exciting to see Chris and Tessa work together again, and seeing Liam Neeson as an MIB agent makes me wonder how they never thought about having him do this before. I think he's an amazing choice to be in the MIB. One thing in the comments section I am seeing is people are irritated by Tessa Thompson's role as an agent when the film is called Men In Black, and I don't really get their point. Yes, she is female. I also understand a female reboot of Ghostbusters came out in 2016 to generally negative reviews from the fan side of things. Firstly, this is not Ghostbusters. We don't know the actual quality of the film we will be receiving, however going off the trailers available this seems to be going in a better direction. Secondly the previous films contained female agents L and O. Agent O is even in this trailer. Lastly, who cares if the title says "Men"? We've had an entire film series called X-Men which starred females as mutants. In any case, these are fiction anyway and can set the rules of their universe however they want. If it comes out and contains "I'm strong because I'm a woman" scenes, then I would see where you are coming from, but this trailer doesn't indicate anything special about her gender, and we don't have the full movie yet. Well now that the rant is out of the way, I'll end by saying I am more interested then I thought I'd actually be for this movie and can't wait to see more of it.

They’ll conform to the identities they give each other, eat where they tell each other, live where they tell each other. From now on, they’ll have no identifying marks of any kind. They will not stand in any way. Their entire images are crafted to leave no lasting memories with any one they encounter. They are a rumor, recognizable only as deja vu,  and dismissed just as quickly. They don’t exist. They were never even born. Anonymity is their name. Silence, their native tongues.
